xture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, BoxList2); // sand surrounding the grass island glBegin(GL_QUADS); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(-4.0f, -0.1f, -4.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(4.0f, -0.1f, -4.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(4.0f, -0.1f, 4.0f); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(-4.0f, -0.1f, 4.0f); glEnd(); // grass island glBegin(GL_QUADS); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(-2.0f, -0.05f, -2.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(2.0f, -0.05f, -2.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(2.0f, -0.05f, 2.0f); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(-2.0f, -0.05f, 2.0f); glEnd(); // disable texturing glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); } ``` Note that the texture coordinates range from 0.0 to 1.0, representing the full width and height of the texture image. The vertex positions are specified in world coordinates, and the glTexCoord2f() calls correspond to the same order of vertices in the glBegin() and glEnd() calls."},{"prompt":"now its thin make it ticker","completion":"To make the island thicker, you can increase the Y component of the scale parameter in the glScalef() calls. Here\'s an example code that makes the island thicker: ```c++ void drawFloor() { // enable texturing glEnable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); // bind the texture glBindTexture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, BoxList2); // sand surrounding the grass island glBegin(GL_QUADS); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(-4.0f, -0.1f, -4.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(4.0f, -0.1f, -4.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(4.0f, -0.1f, 4.0f); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(-4.0f, -0.1f, 4.0f); glEnd(); // grass island glBegin(GL_QUADS); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(-2.0f, -0.05f, -2.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(2.0f, -0.05f, -2.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(2.0f, -0.05f, 2.0f); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(-2.0f, -0.05f, 2.0f); glEnd(); // make the grass island thicker glPushMatrix(); glTranslatef(0.0f, -0.3f, 0.0f); // move down to compensate for the thicker height glScalef(1.2f, 0.6f, 1.2f); // increase the Y scale to make the island thicker glBegin(GL_QUADS); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(-2.0f, 0.0f, -2.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(2.0f, 0.0f, -2.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(2.0f, 0.0f, 2.0f); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(-2.0f, 0.0f, 2.0f); glEnd(); glPopMatrix(); // disable texturing glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); } ``` In this code, we added a new glBegin() and glEnd() block, and we used glTranslatef() to move down and compensate for the thicker height. We also increased the Y component of the glScalef() call to make the island thicker."},{"prompt":"read about islands shapes","completion":"Islands come in different shapes and sizes depending on various factors such as the geological activity, tides, and climate. Here are some common shapes of islands you can find in nature: 1. Atolls: Atolls are circular or oval-shaped islands that are formed from coral reefs. They are typically found in warm, shallow waters and have a central lagoon that is surrounded by land. 2. Volcanic islands: Volcanic islands are formed from volcanic activity and typically have a conical or curved shape. The slopes can be steep or gentle, and the terrain is often uneven and jagged. 3. Barrier islands: Barrier islands are long, narrow islands that run parallel to the mainland coast. They often have a sandy beach on one side and salt marshes or wetlands on the other. 4. Continental islands: Continental islands are large islands that are separated from the mainland by shallow water. They can have a variety of shapes, including circular, oblong, or irregular. 5. Spits: Spits are long, narrow, and often curved strips of land that extend from the mainland into the ocean. They can be formed by sediment deposition or sandbars. 6. Craggy islands: Craggy islands, also known as rocky islands, are islands that have a rugged and uneven coastline with high cliffs and rocky terrain. These types of islands are often found in areas with high tides and strong waves. 7. Artificial islands: Artificial islands are man-made islands created for various purposes, such as expanding land for urban development, creating a habitat for animals, or building a recreational area. They can have a variety of shapes, including circular, rectangular, or irregular."},{"prompt":"create Atolls shaped island example","completion":"Here\'s an example of how to create a basic atoll-shaped island using OpenGL: ```c++ void drawIsland() { glEnable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); glBindTexture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, islandTexture); // bind island texture // draw the atoll-shaped base glPushMatrix(); glTranslatef(0.0f, -0.5f, 0.0f); // position the base in the center glRotatef(-90.0f, 1.0f, 0.0f, 0.0f); // rotate the base to be horizontal GLUquadricObj* base = gluNewQuadric(); gluQuadricTexture(base, true); gluQuadricNormals(base, GLU_SMOOTH); gluCylinder(base, 4.0f, 8.0f, 2.0f, 32, 1); gluDeleteQuadric(base); glPopMatrix(); // draw the main island glPushMatrix(); glTranslatef(0.0f, 1.0f, 0.0f); // position the island on top of the base glScalef(2.0f, 1.0f, 2.0f); // make the island slightly elongated GLUquadricObj* island = gluNewQuadric(); gluQuadricTexture(island, true); gluQuadricNormals(island, GLU_SMOOTH); gluSphere(island, 4.0f, 32, 32); gluDeleteQuadric(island); glPopMatrix(); glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); } ``` This code creates an atoll shape by using a cylinder as the base and a sphere as the main island. The base is positioned in the center and rotated to be horizontal. A texture is applied to both the base and the island. The island is slightly elongated using glScalef() and placed on top of the base using glTranslatef()."},{"prompt":"create Asia shaped island","completion":"Here\'s an example of how to create an Asia-shaped island using OpenGL: ```c++ void drawIsland() { glEnable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); glBindTexture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, islandTexture); // bind island texture // draw the base glPushMatrix(); GLUquadricObj* base = gluNewQuadric(); gluQuadricTexture(base, true); gluQuadricNormals(base, GLU_SMOOTH); gluDisk(base, 0.0f, 8.0f, 32, 1); // draw a disk for the main land gluCylinder(base, 0.0f, 5.5f, 2.0f, 32, 1); // draw a narrow cylinder to form the southeastern part of the island gluCylinder(base, 0.0f, 3.5f, 2.0f, 32, 1); // draw a narrower cylinder to form the northern and eastern parts of the island gluDeleteQuadric(base); glPopMatrix(); // draw the mountain ranges glPushMatrix(); GLUquadricObj* mountains = gluNewQuadric(); gluQuadricTexture(mountains, true); gluQuadricNormals(mountains, GLU_SMOOTH); glTranslatef(0.0f, 0.0f, 1.0f); // move up from the base gluCylinder(mountains, 2.0f, 3.0f, 2.0f, 32, 1); // draw a taller cylinder for the main mountain range glTranslatef(0.0f, 0.0f, 2.0f); // move up to draw a second mountain range gluCylinder(mountains, 1.0f, 2.0f, 2.0f, 32, 1); gluDeleteQuadric(mountains); glPopMatrix(); glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); } ``` In this code, the base of the island is created using a combination of gluDisk() and gluCylinder() calls to form the shape of Asia, with a narrower cylindrical shape to form the southeastern part of the island, and a narrower cylindrical shape to form the northern and eastern parts of the island. A texture is applied to the island base. The mountain ranges are created using a separate GLUquadricObj object, with glTranslatef() used to move up and draw two different heights of cylinder. Finally, the texture is disabled using glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D)."},{"prompt":"create asia geography","completion":"Here\'s an example of how to create Asia\'s geography using OpenGL: ```c++ void drawGeography() { glEnable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); glBindTexture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, mountainTexture); // bind mountain texture // draw the Himalayas glPushMatrix(); glTranslatef(0.0f, 2.0f, 0.0f); // move up from the base glBegin(GL_QUADS); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(-5.0f, -2.0f, -5.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(5.0f, -2.0f, -5.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(5.0f, -2.0f, 5.0f); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(-5.0f, -2.0f, 5.0f); glEnd(); glPopMatrix(); // draw the Aral Sea glPushMatrix(); glTranslatef(-6.0f, -0.5f, -6.0f); // position the sea to the left of the island glBegin(GL_QUADS); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(0.0f, 0.0f, 0.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(12.0f, 0.0f, 0.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(12.0f, 0.0f, 12.0f); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(0.0f, 0.0f, 12.0f); glEnd(); glPopMatrix(); // draw the Gobi Desert glPushMatrix(); glTranslatef(-5.5f, -0.5f, 5.5f); // position the desert to the northwest of the island glBegin(GL_QUADS); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(0.0f, -1.0f, 0.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 0.0f); glVertex3f(11.0f, -1.0f, 0.0f); glTexCoord2f(1.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(11.0f, -1.0f, 11.0f); glTexCoord2f(0.0f, 1.0f); glVertex3f(0.0f, -1.0f, 11.0f); glEnd(); glPopMatrix(); glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); } ``` In this code, we create three different parts of Asia\'s geography: the Himalayas, the Aral Sea, and the Gobi Desert. Each section is drawn using a combination of glTranslatef() calls to position the object and glTexCoord2f() calls to apply a texture to the object. The actual geometry of each section is created using a GL_QUADS glBegin() / glEnd() block with four endpoints for the corners of a square. We use glBindTexture() to apply different textures to different parts of the island, such as mountainTexture for the Himalayas."},{"prompt":"create a mountin","completion":"Here\'s an example of how to create a basic mountain using OpenGL: ```c++ void drawMountain() { glEnable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); glBindTexture(GL_TEXTURE_2D, mountainTexture); // bind mountain texture GLUquadricObj* mountain = gluNewQuadric(); gluQuadricTexture(mountain, true); // enable texture mapping gluQuadricNormals(mountain, GLU_SMOOTH); // set the normal vectors to smooth the lighting // draw the mountain as a cone glPushMatrix(); glRotatef(-90.0f, 1.0f, 0.0f, 0.0f); // rotate the cone to be vertical gluCylinder(mountain, 0.0f, 2.0f, 4.0f, 32, 1); glPopMatrix(); gluDeleteQuadric(mountain); glDisable(GL_TEXTURE_2D); } ``` This code creates a GLUquadricObj object and sets it up for texture mapping and smooth normals. A cone is created using gluCylinder(), with the base radius set to 0.0f to make it pointy like a mountain. The texture is applied using glBindTexture() and a specific texture coordinate is mapped to each vertex of the mountain in texture space based on the object geometry."},{"prompt":"Generate 20 new brand name ideas for my company called soskill but don’t include the work kill in it. It is a model figure company","completion":"1. SoPose 2. SoStat 3. SoModel 4. SoPro 5. SoCharisma 6. SoArticulate 7. SoElegance 8. SoMastery 9. SoCharm 10. SoSolution 11. SoImpeccable 12. SoPrecision 13. SoExpert 14. SoDexterity 15. SoRefinement 16. SoProficient 17. SoTalent 18. SoFlair 19. SoAcumen 20. SoGraceful"},{"prompt":"create an example of a cloud in opengl","completion":"As an AI language model, I cannot create graphics, but I can provide you with the OpenGL code that can be used to create a basic cloud: ``` #include <GL/glut.h> void renderCloud() { glColor3f(1.0, 1.0, 1.0); glutSolidSphere(1, 50, 50); // create a sphere with a radius of 1 } void display() { glClear(GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT); glMatrixMode(GL_MODELVIEW); glLoadIdentity(); glTranslatef(0.0f, 0.0f, -5.0f); // move the sphere away from the camera for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) { glPushMatrix(); glTranslatef(rand() % 10 - 5, rand() % 2 - 1, rand() % 10 - 5); // randomly position each sphere renderCloud(); glPopMatrix(); } glutSwapBuffers(); } void reshape(int width, int height) { glViewport(0, 0, (GLsizei)width, (GLsizei)height); glMatrixMode(GL_PROJECTION); glLoadIdentity(); gluPerspective(45.0, (GLfloat)width / (GLfloat)height, 0.1, 100.0); } int main(int argc, char** argv) { glutInit(&argc, argv); glutInitDisplayMode(GLUT_DOUBLE | GLUT_RGBA); glutInitWindowSize(640, 480); glutInitWindowPosition(100, 100); glutCreateWindow(\\"Cloud Example\\"); glutDisplayFunc(display); glutReshapeFunc(reshape); glutMainLoop(); return 0; } ``` The code above creates a simple cloud by drawing multiple spheres with a radius of 1, each positioned at random locations in 3D space. OpenGL\'s built-in `glutSolidSphere()` function is used to create each sphere. The `glTranslatef()` function is used to position each sphere. `glPushMatrix()` and `glPopMatrix()` are used to preserve and restore the current transformation matrix, so that each sphere can be positioned independently. Finally, the `gluPerspective()` function is used to set up a perspective projection."},{"prompt":"Код на java. Нужно создать класс University в Main и сделать ему значения учеников, учмтелкй и предметов, потом вывести их","completion":"public class University { private String[] students; private String[] teachers; private String[] subjects; public University(String[] students, String[] teachers, String[] subjects) { this.students = students; this.teachers = teachers; this.subjects = subjects; } public String[] getStudents() { return students; } public void setStudents(String[] students) { this.students = students; } public String[] getTeachers() { return teachers; } public void setTeachers(String[] teachers) { this.teachers = teachers; } public String[] getSubjects() { return subjects; } public void setSubjects(String[] subjects) { this.subjects = subjects; } } public class Main { public static void main(String[] args) { String[] students = {\\"John\\", \\"Mary\\", \\"Tom\\"}; String[] teachers = {\\"Mr. Johnson\\", \\"Mrs. Smith\\"}; String[] subjects = {\\"Math\\", \\"English\\"}; University university = new University(students, teachers, subjects); System.out.println(\\"Students:\\"); for(String student : university.getStudents()) { System.out.println(student); } System.out.println(\\"Teachers:\\"); for(String teacher : university.getTeachers()) { System.out.println(teacher); } System.out.println(\\"Subjects:\\"); for(String subject : university.getSubjects()) { System.out.println(subject); } } }"},{"prompt":"Очень сложно, намного, намного легче и короче можно","completion":"Конечно, вот более короткий вариант: ```java public class University { public static void main(String[] args) { String[] students = {\\"John\\", \\"Mary\\", \\"Tom\\"}; String[] teachers = {\\"Mr. Johnson\\", \\"Mrs. Smith\\"}; String[] subjects = {\\"Math\\", \\"English\\"}; System.out.println(\\"Students:\\"); for(String student : students) { System.out.println(student); } System.out.println(\\"Teachers:\\"); for(String teacher : teachers) { System.out.println(teacher); } System.out.println(\\"Subjects:\\"); for(String subject : subjects) { System.out.println(subject); } } } ``` Этот код создает 3 массива из строк, и затем выводит их значения."},{"prompt":"应该选哪个答案：4. -- ________ can you finish this English examination? -- In about one and a half hours. A. How far B. How often C. How soon D. How long","completion":"D. How long"},{"prompt":"为什么，","completion":"因为题干问的是完成考试需要多长时间，而\\"How long\\"可以用来询问时间长度。而其他选项中\\"How far\\"通常用来询问距离，\\"How often\\"用来询问频率，\\"How soon\\"用来询问时间的紧迫程度。因此，正确答案是D. How long。"},{"prompt":"You are an expert in strategic analysis of companies in the e-commerce sector. Can you provide an analysis of the political factors impacting Amazon e-commerce’s business strategy, using events, news and trends from the past 3 years, citing your sources.","completion":"Over the past three years, several political factors have significantly impacted Amazon\'s e-commerce business strategy. 1. Antitrust investigations & regulations: Governments and regulators across different countries have been scrutinizing big tech companies, including Amazon, due to concerns over market dominance practices. In 2020, the European Union opened a formal antitrust investigation into Amazon\'s practices, such as abusing its dual role as both a marketplace for independent sellers and a retailer of its own products (European Commission, 2020). Similarly, in the United States, the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) has also been investigating whether Amazon has an unfair advantage and stifles competition (Reuters, 2020). These political factors can bring about new regulations and compliance measures that can impact Amazon\'s business strategy and operations. Sources: - European Commission (2020) - https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_20_1072 - Reuters (2020) - https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amazon-com-ftc-exclusive-idUSKBN1ZT0CC 2. Taxation policies: In recent years, Amazon has faced criticism for its tax practices and has been under pressure from various governments to pay its fair share of taxes. In 2018, the United States government introduced a new tax reform impacting American corporations\' taxation, including Amazon. Additionally, the EU introduced a Digital Services Tax (DST) on technology companies, which specifically targeted big tech firms like Amazon, to ensure they pay taxes where they generate substantial revenues (European Commission, 2020). These taxation policies may affect Amazon\'s profitability and may require adjustments to its prices and product offerings. Source: European Commission (2020) - https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_20_972 3. Data protection regulations: Stricter data protection regulations like the European Union\'s General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) have obliged e-commerce companies like Amazon to strengthen their data protection and privacy measures. Non-compliance with GDPR can lead to heavy fines and reputational damage, which would influence Amazon\'s business strategy as the company may need to invest in new systems and processes to ensure compliance. Source: EU GDPR (2016) - https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:32016R0679 4. Trade policies & tariffs: The trade war between the United States and China has led to increased tariffs and restrictions on imports and exports, affecting Amazon\'s e-commerce business, as it relies on sourcing products and selling them globally. The tariffs lead to increased costs for Amazon\'s business, which may influence its pricing decisions and prompt shifts in its supply chain strategy. Source: CNBC (2019) - https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/14/amazon-to-lower-some-fees-it-charges-sellers-open-new-shipping-option.html 5. Brexit: Brexit has created uncertainties in Amazon\'s European operations due to potential regulatory and compliance changes. Amazon has had to adjust its business strategy, including setting up an independent fulfillment center in the UK to counter potential disruptions to its supply chain and logistic operations. Sources: - Reuters (2020) - https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-amazon/businesses-expect-brexit-events-foreshadow-third-country-rules-amazon-idUSKBN20A30J - The Telegraph (2020) - https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2020/12/03/amazon-waste-no-time-cutting-uk-small-businesses-brexit/ In conclusion, the political factors that have impacted Amazon\'s e-commerce business strategy over the past three years include antitrust investigations and regulations, taxation policies, data protection regulations, trade policies and tariffs, and Brexit. These factors have required Amazon to adapt its business operations to accommodate various political changes, influences, and regulations."},{"prompt":"You are an expert in strategic analysis of companies in the e-commerce sector. Can you provide an analysis of the economic factors impacting Amazon e-commerce’s business strategy, using events, news and trends from the past 3 years, citing your sources.","completion":"Over the past three years, several economic factors have significantly impacted Amazon\'s e-commerce business strategy. 1. Macroeconomic factors: Global economic growth and consumer spending patterns directly influence Amazon\'s e-commerce business. A healthy and growing economy results in higher consumer spending, benefiting e-commerce platforms like Amazon. However, factors such as an economic slowdown or recession can have negative effects on business growth. As the COVID-19 pandemic hit the global economy in 2020, Amazon experienced increased demand due to people shopping online during lockdowns, but faced challenges in managing supply chains and meeting customer expectations (Amazon, 2020). Source: Amazon (2020) - https://ir.aboutamazon.com/static-files/b4857e8c-f01e-4a16-b6a3-b6de8ea726e4 2. Currency exchange rates: Amazon\'s international operations expose the company to currency exchange rate fluctuations that can impact its profitability. A strong US dollar affects Amazon\'s non-US sales when converted back to dollars, resulting in lower reported revenue. Amazon may also have to adjust its pricing strategies to be competitive in local markets where the local currency has depreciated against the dollar. Source: Amazon (2019) - https://ir.aboutamazon.com/static-files/98f15822-0fc9-40fc-8733-0c528b0cc43f 3. Inflation and interest rates: Inflation and interest rates directly impact consumer spending and influence business operating expenses. Amazon may face higher costs of capital when interest rates increase, affecting its capital expenditure and expansion plans. On the other hand, lower interest rates can make borrowing cheaper and create opportunities for the company to invest in growth initiatives. Source: Knoema (2021) - https://knoema.com//atlas/United-States/Interest-rate 4. Government fiscal policies: Government fiscal policies, such as changes in tax rates and public expenditure, have a direct impact on Amazon\'s business strategy. For instance, the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act in the United States significantly lowered the corporate tax rate, enhancing Amazon\'s profitability and shifting its approach to capital investment (Amazon, 2017). Conversely, the introduction of digital taxes in various countries, such as France and the United Kingdom, increases the tax burden on Amazon and may affect its pricing and expansion strategies (European Commission, 2020). Sources: - Amazon (2017) - https://ir.aboutamazon.com/static-files/3d6f16e6-48fe-49de-8c3a-9136149c57f0 - European Commission (2020) - https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_20_972 5. Infrastructure and technology adoption trends: Economic factors such as infrastructure development and technology adoption rates play a vital role in shaping Amazon\'s e-commerce strategy. The growth of internet infrastructure, smartphone penetration, and increasing digital literacy levels directly influence Amazon\'s potential customer base and the success of its e-commerce platform. Moreover, Amazon\'s investments in artificial intelligence, automation, and drone delivery systems represent attempts to adapt to evolving technological trends and stay ahead of its competitors (Amazon, 2020). Source: Amazon (2020) - https://www.aboutamazon.com/news/innovation-at-amazon/amazon-now-has-200-000-robots-working-in-its-warehouses In conclusion, the economic factors that have impacted Amazon\'s e-commerce business strategy over the past three years include macroeconomic factors, currency exchange rates, inflation and interest rates, government fiscal policies, and infrastructure and technology adoption trends. These factors have required Amazon to adapt its business approach to be competitive, maintain profitability, and drive growth in an evolving global economic landscape."},{"prompt":"股市有什么利好消息","completion":"作为语言模型AI，我不会考虑或掌握当前或潜在的市场情况或事件，建议您关注财经新闻或专业人士提供的市场信息和评论，以获取最新资讯和投资建议。"},{"prompt":"你就说大盘的利好消息，不需要预测","completion":"好的，以下是最近发生的一些大盘利好消息： 1. 中国经济表现强劲，第一季度GDP同比增长18.3%，超过预期。 2. 美国宣布推出近2万亿美元的基础设施计划，可能对全球经济产生积极影响。 3. 央行降准，释放流动性，有利于支持实体经济发展。 4. 我国加快推进新能源等绿色产业发展，蓝筹股关注度有所提高。 5. 疫苗研发及接种进展顺利，疫情控制体系逐步完善，对于经济复苏提供支持。 需要注意的是，以上利好消息只是个例，并不代表未来一定会发生类似的利好事件。"},{"prompt":"Potresti interrogarmi su uno di questi argomenti? Introduzione alle finalità del corso. Modalitàdi svolgimento del